---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import AdUnit from '../../components/AdUnit.astro';
import { getWorksheetBySlug } from '../../data/worksheets';
import '../../styles/worksheet.css';

const ws = getWorksheetBySlug('proportions-worksheets')!;

const structuredData = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
  "itemListElement": [
    {
      "@type": "ListItem",
      "position": 1,
      "name": "Home",
      "item": "https://toolcalcs.com/"
    },
    {
      "@type": "ListItem",
      "position": 2,
      "name": "Worksheets",
      "item": "https://toolcalcs.com/worksheets/"
    },
    {
      "@type": "ListItem",
      "position": 3,
      "name": "Proportions Worksheets"
    }
  ]
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Free Proportions Worksheets - Printable Math Practice | ToolCalcs"
  description={ws.description}
  type="article"
  structuredData={structuredData}
>
  <nav class="breadcrumb">
    <a href="/">Home</a> &rsaquo;
    <a href="/worksheets/">Worksheets</a> &rsaquo;
    <span>Proportions Worksheets</span>
  </nav>

  <h1>{ws.title}</h1>
  <p class="page-desc">{ws.description}</p>

  <div class="worksheet-box">
    <div class="config-panel">
      <h3>Settings</h3>
      <div class="config-inputs">
        <div class="config-group">
          <label for="cfgProblems">Number of Problems</label>
          <input type="number" id="cfgProblems" value="15" min="5" max="30" />
        </div>
        <div class="config-group">
          <label for="cfgDifficulty">Difficulty</label>
          <select id="cfgDifficulty">
            <option value="easy" selected>Easy</option>
            <option value="medium">Medium</option>
            <option value="hard">Hard</option>
          </select>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="worksheet-actions">
      <button class="ws-btn primary" id="btnGenerate">Generate New</button>
      <button class="ws-btn print" id="btnPrint">Print</button>
      <label class="toggle-label">
        <input type="checkbox" id="toggleAnswers" />
        Show Answers
      </label>
    </div>

    <div class="worksheet-content" id="worksheetContent">
      <div class="worksheet-header-print">
        <h2>Proportions Practice</h2>
        <div class="name-date">
          <span>Name: ___________________</span>
          <span>Date: ___________________</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-grid" id="problemGrid"></div>
      <div class="answer-key hidden" id="answerKey">
        <h3>Answer Key</h3>
        <div class="answer-grid" id="answerGrid"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <AdUnit slot="ws-mid" format="rectangle" />

  <article class="content-section">
    <h2>What Are Proportions?</h2>
    <p>A proportion is an equation that states two ratios are equal. It takes the form a/b = c/d, where a, b, c, and d are numbers and neither b nor d is zero. Proportions are one of the most practical mathematical concepts students encounter in middle school because they model real-world relationships everywhere: scaling recipes, converting units, reading maps, calculating rates, and solving percent problems. When students master proportions, they gain a versatile problem-solving tool that serves them throughout algebra and beyond.</p>
    <p>These free printable proportions worksheets provide unlimited practice with solving proportions in the standard form a/b = c/x. Each problem presents three known values and one unknown, and students must use cross-multiplication or equivalent-ratio reasoning to find the missing value. The configurable difficulty setting controls the size and complexity of the numbers involved, making these worksheets suitable for students in grades 6 through 8.</p>

    <h2>How to Solve Proportions</h2>
    <h3>Cross-Multiplication</h3>
    <p>The most common method for solving proportions is cross-multiplication. Given the proportion a/b = c/x, multiply the numerator of each fraction by the denominator of the other: a times x equals b times c. Then solve the resulting equation for x by dividing both sides by a. For example, to solve 3/4 = 6/x, cross-multiply to get 3x = 24, then divide both sides by 3 to find x = 8.</p>
    <p>Cross-multiplication works because multiplying both sides of an equation by the same value preserves equality. When you multiply a/b = c/x by both b and x, the denominators cancel and you are left with ax = bc. This algebraic justification helps students understand why the shortcut works rather than simply memorizing a procedure.</p>

    <h3>Scale Factor Method</h3>
    <p>An alternative approach is to find the scale factor between the two ratios. If a/b = c/x, determine what number you multiply a by to get c (the scale factor is c/a), then multiply b by the same factor to find x. This method reinforces the concept that proportional relationships involve a constant multiplier and connects proportions to the broader idea of linear scaling.</p>

    <h2>Grade-Level Expectations</h2>
    <h3>Grade 6 (Ages 11-12)</h3>
    <p>Sixth graders are introduced to ratios and proportional reasoning. They learn to write ratios, identify equivalent ratios, and solve simple proportions with small whole numbers. Use the Easy difficulty to generate problems with manageable numbers that let students focus on the method rather than the arithmetic.</p>

    <h3>Grade 7 (Ages 12-13)</h3>
    <p>Seventh graders formalize proportional relationships and connect them to unit rates, percentages, and linear equations. They solve proportions with larger numbers and apply proportional reasoning to real-world contexts. Use the Medium difficulty for practice with numbers that require more careful computation.</p>

    <h3>Grade 8 (Ages 13-14)</h3>
    <p>Eighth graders apply proportional reasoning in geometry (similar figures, scale drawings) and algebra. They work with proportions involving larger numbers and multi-step problems. Use the Hard difficulty for challenging practice that builds fluency and prepares students for high school algebra.</p>

    <h2>Tips for Parents and Teachers</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Teach cross-multiplication as a shortcut, not a mystery.</strong> Show students why it works by multiplying both sides of the equation by both denominators. Understanding the algebra behind the shortcut prevents errors and builds mathematical reasoning.</li>
      <li><strong>Use real-world contexts.</strong> Have students set up proportions from recipe scaling, map reading, and unit conversion problems before practicing the abstract form. Context makes the concept meaningful and memorable.</li>
      <li><strong>Check answers by substituting back.</strong> After finding x, have students plug it back into the original proportion and verify that both fractions are equal. This self-checking habit catches computational errors and reinforces the meaning of equality.</li>
      <li><strong>Start with Easy difficulty.</strong> Build confidence with small numbers before progressing to Medium and Hard. Accuracy is more important than speed when learning a new concept.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Related Worksheets</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/ratio-and-proportion-worksheets/">Ratio &amp; Proportion Worksheets</a> &ndash; Practice equivalent ratios and simplifying ratios.</li>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/percentages-worksheets/">Percentages Worksheets</a> &ndash; Apply proportional reasoning to percent problems.</li>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/fractions-worksheets/">Fractions Worksheets</a> &ndash; Build fraction fluency that supports proportion work.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>

  <AdUnit slot="ws-bottom" format="horizontal" />
</BaseLayout>

<script is:inline>
  var problems = [];

  function randInt(min, max) {
    return Math.floor(Math.random() * (max - min + 1)) + min;
  }

  function generateProblems() {
    var count = parseInt(document.getElementById('cfgProblems').value, 10);
    var difficulty = document.getElementById('cfgDifficulty').value;

    if (isNaN(count) || count < 5) count = 5;
    if (count > 30) count = 30;

    var maxVal;
    if (difficulty === 'easy') maxVal = 12;
    else if (difficulty === 'medium') maxVal = 30;
    else maxVal = 60;

    problems = [];

    for (var i = 0; i < count; i++) {
      // Generate a/b = c/x where x = b*c/a (must be integer)
      var a = randInt(2, maxVal);
      var b = randInt(2, maxVal);
      var multiplier = randInt(2, Math.max(2, Math.floor(maxVal / Math.max(a, b))));
      // Ensure we get integer answer
      var c = a * multiplier;
      var x = b * multiplier;

      // Randomly decide which position is unknown
      var pos = randInt(0, 3);
      var text, answer;

      if (pos === 0) {
        // a is unknown: ?/b = c/x
        text = '? / ' + b + ' = ' + c + ' / ' + x;
        answer = a;
      } else if (pos === 1) {
        // b is unknown: a/? = c/x
        text = a + ' / ? = ' + c + ' / ' + x;
        answer = b;
      } else if (pos === 2) {
        // c is unknown: a/b = ?/x
        text = a + ' / ' + b + ' = ? / ' + x;
        answer = c;
      } else {
        // x is unknown: a/b = c/?
        text = a + ' / ' + b + ' = ' + c + ' / ?';
        answer = x;
      }

      problems.push({ text: text, answer: answer });
    }

    renderProblems();
    renderAnswerKey();
    updateAnswerVisibility();
  }

  function renderProblems() {
    var grid = document.getElementById('problemGrid');
    var showAnswers = document.getElementById('toggleAnswers').checked;
    var html = '';

    for (var i = 0; i < problems.length; i++) {
      var p = problems[i];
      html += '<div class="problem">';
      html += '<div class="problem-number">' + (i + 1) + ')</div>';
      html += '<div class="problem-text">' + p.text + '</div>';
      html += '<div class="problem-answer' + (showAnswers ? ' revealed' : '') + '">';
      html += showAnswers ? p.answer : '___';
      html += '</div>';
      html += '</div>';
    }

    grid.innerHTML = html;
  }

  function renderAnswerKey() {
    var answerGrid = document.getElementById('answerGrid');
    var html = '';
    for (var i = 0; i < problems.length; i++) {
      html += '<div class="answer-item"><span class="q">' + (i + 1) + '.</span><span class="a">' + problems[i].answer + '</span></div>';
    }
    answerGrid.innerHTML = html;
  }

  function updateAnswerVisibility() {
    var showAnswers = document.getElementById('toggleAnswers').checked;
    var answerKey = document.getElementById('answerKey');
    if (showAnswers) { answerKey.classList.remove('hidden'); } else { answerKey.classList.add('hidden'); }
    renderProblems();
  }

  document.getElementById('btnGenerate').addEventListener('click', generateProblems);
  document.getElementById('btnPrint').addEventListener('click', function() { window.print(); });
  document.getElementById('toggleAnswers').addEventListener('change', updateAnswerVisibility);
  generateProblems();
</script>
